Case Study #1¶

This data set represents thousands of loans made through the Lending Club platform, which is a platform that allows individuals to lend to other individuals. Of course, not all loans are created equal. Someone who is a essentially a sure bet to pay back a loan will have an easier time getting a loan with a low interest rate than someone who appears to be riskier. And for people who are very risky? They may not even get a loan offer, or they may not have accepted the loan offer due to a high interest rate. It is important to keep that last part in mind, since this data set only represents loans actually made, i.e. do not mistake this data for loan applications!

Filling Missing values¶

I will ommit variables that have many missing values and for those who are a few, I will try fill some of them trying to understand what is missing.

In [9]:
# emp_length is the Number of years in the job, rounded down. 
# If longer than 10 years, then this is represented by the value 10.
# I believe that a mistake with the rounding process has happened and
# thus the missing values appeared
df['emp_length'].fillna(0, inplace=True)

# same concept and for the rest of the variables
# I believe that they need to replace the NA values with zero
# since the missing values they have, describe information that was ommitted
# to be entered and most probably based on the date described by these variables
# they describe lack of information when NA values occurs, 
# so zero is most appropriate value to fill there.

df['debt_to_income'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
df['annual_income_joint'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
df['months_since_last_delinq'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
df['months_since_90d_late'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
df['months_since_last_credit_inquiry'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
df['num_accounts_120d_past_due'].fillna(0, inplace=True);

Machine Learning Models¶

Preparing feature set before building predictive models¶

Since we have many categorical variables, we need to encode them in order to be suitable for building models later on. Thus I used the one-hot-encoding technique to turn all the categorical variables into numerical encoded variables.

In [32]:
df.drop(['emp_title'], axis=1) # droping the name of the Job title

df_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df.select_dtypes(exclude=[np.number]))
df_new = pd.concat([df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]), df_dummies], axis=1)

Seperating the features X and the response variable y

In [33]:
y = df_new["interest_rate"] # response variable
X = df_new.drop(['interest_rate'], axis=1, inplace=False)

KNeighborsRegressor model¶

I will use the Knn model (K-Nearest neighbors) for regression. The target is predicted by local interpolation of the targets associated of the nearest neighbors in the training set.

I will split the train set X, and the validation set y into 10 folds and using cross validation will evaluate the performance of the model with the MAE metric (Mean absolute error score).

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.neighbors.KNeighborsRegressor.html

In [34]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score


KNeighborsRegressor_clc = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=4)
KNeighborsRegressor_scores = cross_val_score(KNeighborsRegressor_clc, X, y, cv=10, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error', n_jobs=-1, verbose=1)

[Parallel(n_jobs=-1)]: Using backend LokyBackend with 4 concurrent workers.
[Parallel(n_jobs=-1)]: Done  10 out of  10 | elapsed:   35.6s finished
In [35]:
print("Mean score of %0.2f with a standard deviation of %0.2f" % ((-1)*KNeighborsRegressor_scores.mean(), 
                                                                  KNeighborsRegressor_scores.std()))

Mean score of 3.88 with a standard deviation of 0.10

Knn model is very fast, it took 34 seconds to evaluate all folds. Mean MAE score is 3.88 and std of scores are 0.10.

Random Forest model¶

I will use the Random Forest model for regression. Random Forest is an ensemble learning method for classification and regression and it is based on the bagging of the training set.

I will again split the train set X, and the validation set y into 10 folds and using cross validation will evaluate the performance of the model with the MAE metric (Mean absolute error score).

In [36]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score


random_forest_clc = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=1, max_depth=6, n_estimators=50, n_jobs=-1)
random_forest_scores = cross_val_score(random_forest_clc, X, y, cv=10, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error', n_jobs=-1, verbose=1)

[Parallel(n_jobs=-1)]: Using backend LokyBackend with 4 concurrent workers.
[Parallel(n_jobs=-1)]: Done  10 out of  10 | elapsed:  2.5min finished
In [37]:
print("Mean score of %0.2f with a standard deviation of %0.2f" % ((-1)*random_forest_scores.mean(), random_forest_scores.std()))

Mean score of 0.12 with a standard deviation of 0.01

Random forest model is slower than Knn, it took 2.5 minutes to evaluate all folds. Mean MAE score is 0.12 and std of scores are 0.01.

Conclusion and future suggestions¶

Random Forest shows better accuracy than kNN model. It had less error and the std. of errors were insignificant small.

In order to improve my models more I would like to reduce the amount of variables used for training. Maybe using the correlation table to choose those who correlation more with the interest_rate.

Moreover, I would like to find out the most important features after building training our models. Which features are these that have more impact to make predictions or they have a larger effect on the model that is being used to predict a certain variable.

Finally I would like to perform a tuning to my models to find better optimal parameters for the models to reduce the error of prediction even more.
